{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18158"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18158"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.63,0,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10872"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59152"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7383"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"},{"type":"tags","id":"11414"},{"type":"tags","id":"11422"},{"type":"tags","id":"11423"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute shoulder pain that started two days ago. She reports a recent minor trauma to the shoulder while lifting a heavy object. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. The shoulder is swollen and tender, with limited range of motion due to pain. Investigations reveal deposition of hydroxyapatite crystals in the shoulder, with associated swelling and intense inflammation, mimicking infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely pathology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adhesive capsulitis","Calcific tendinitis","Shoulder instability","Rotator cuff tear","Frozen shoulder"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and investigation findings are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcific tendinitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by the deposition of calcium hydroxyapatite crystals in the tendons, most commonly affecting the rotator cuff. The acute pain and inflammation can mimic infection, and minor trauma can precipitate symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdhesive capsulitis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as frozen shoulder, typically presents with gradual onset of shoulder stiffness and pain, rather than acute pain and swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShoulder instability\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with a history of dislocations or subluxations, not acute inflammation and crystal deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotator cuff tear\u003C/strong\u003E often results from trauma or degeneration and presents with weakness and pain, but not with crystal deposition or intense inflammation mimicking infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrozen shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E is another term for adhesive capsulitis, which is characterised by stiffness and gradual pain, not acute inflammation due to crystal deposition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Calcific tendinitis is characterised by the deposition of calcium hydroxyapatite crystals in the tendons, most commonly affecting the rotator cuff.","The condition can cause acute shoulder pain and inflammation, often mimicking infection.","Minor trauma can precipitate symptoms in individuals with calcific tendinitis."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59152"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18158"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59152"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T01:20:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T16:08:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10872"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions",